<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="229" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="32.[212,817,1759,2072]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[212,365,1759,1783]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Redescription</emphasis>
: Body length 
<quantity box="[522,653,1760,1784]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="32" pageNumber="229" unit="mm" value="2.4" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.3">2.3–2.5 mm</quantity>
; length of forebody 
<quantity box="[273,404,1792,1816]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="32" pageNumber="229" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.1">1.1–1.2 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[563,625,1792,1816]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="33.[174,214,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-510@33.[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figs 6–10: Stichoglossa graeca from Crete: habitus (6); forebody (7); male abdominal tergites VII–VIII (8); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (9–10). Scale bars: 6: 1.0 mm; 7: 0.5 mm; 8: 0.2 mm; 9–10: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4755232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4755232/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
. Coloration: head blackish-brown; pronotum bright reddish; elytra brown with the humeral angles and the postero-sutural portions diffusely yellowish; abdomen blackish with the anterior segments slightly paler and with the posterior portion of segment VII and all of segments VIII–X yellowish; legs yellowish; antennae dark-reddish with the basal two antennomeres slightly paler; maxillary palpi yellowish with palpomere III weakly infuscate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[854,1460,256,1272]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[930,991,256,280]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="33.[174,214,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-510@33.[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figs 6–10: Stichoglossa graeca from Crete: habitus (6); forebody (7); male abdominal tergites VII–VIII (8); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (9–10). Scale bars: 6: 1.0 mm; 7: 0.5 mm; 8: 0.2 mm; 9–10: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4755232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4755232/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) approximately as broad as long; punctation rather sparse and very fine, barely visible in the pronounced microreticulation. Eyes moderately large, slightly shorter than postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna 
<quantity box="[953,1048,384,408]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="32" pageNumber="229" unit="mm" value="0.65">0.65 mm</quantity>
long and distinctly incrassate apically; antennomeres IV distinctly transverse, V–X of increasing width and increasingly transverse, X approximately three times as broad as long, and XI of conical shape, slightly longer than the combined length of IX and X.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[854,1460,256,1272]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[983,1044,544,568]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="33.[174,214,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-510@33.[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figs 6–10: Stichoglossa graeca from Crete: habitus (6); forebody (7); male abdominal tergites VII–VIII (8); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (9–10). Scale bars: 6: 1.0 mm; 7: 0.5 mm; 8: 0.2 mm; 9–10: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4755232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4755232/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) 1.2 times as broad as long and 1.2 times as broad as head; posterior angles obtusely marked; punctation fine and moderately dense, barely visible in the pronounced microreticulation.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[854,1460,256,1272]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[937,998,672,696]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="33.[174,214,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-510@33.[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figs 6–10: Stichoglossa graeca from Crete: habitus (6); forebody (7); male abdominal tergites VII–VIII (8); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (9–10). Scale bars: 6: 1.0 mm; 7: 0.5 mm; 8: 0.2 mm; 9–10: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4755232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4755232/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) as long as pronotum; punctation dense, more distinct than that of head and pronotum; interstices with microsculpture, but glossy. Hind wings fully developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[854,1460,256,1272]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Abdomen narrower than elytra; anterior impressions of tergites III–V shallow; punctation dense and distinct on tergite III, gradually decreasing in density towards posterior tergites, sparse on tergite VII; interstices with shallow microsculpture and glossy; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[854,1460,256,1272]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">
♂: tergite VII (
<figureCitation box="[1027,1087,992,1016]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="33.[174,214,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-510@33.[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figs 6–10: Stichoglossa graeca from Crete: habitus (6); forebody (7); male abdominal tergites VII–VIII (8); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (9–10). Scale bars: 6: 1.0 mm; 7: 0.5 mm; 8: 0.2 mm; 9–10: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4755232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4755232/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) with small, but distinct median tubercle; tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[1098,1158,1024,1048]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="33.[174,214,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-510@33.[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figs 6–10: Stichoglossa graeca from Crete: habitus (6); forebody (7); male abdominal tergites VII–VIII (8); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (9–10). Scale bars: 6: 1.0 mm; 7: 0.5 mm; 8: 0.2 mm; 9–10: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4755232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4755232/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) with small median tubercle posteriorly, posterior margin concave and distinctly serrate; sternite VIII obtusely produced in the middle; median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1131,1237,1120,1144]" captionStart="Figs 6–10" captionStartId="33.[174,214,1091,1113]" captionTargetBox="[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-510@33.[174,1421,255,1089]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="Figs 6–10: Stichoglossa graeca from Crete: habitus (6); forebody (7); male abdominal tergites VII–VIII (8); median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (9–10). Scale bars: 6: 1.0 mm; 7: 0.5 mm; 8: 0.2 mm; 9–10: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4755232" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4755232/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Figs 9–10</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[1251,1346,1120,1144]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="32" pageNumber="229" unit="mm" value="0.23">0.23 mm</quantity>
long, with broad ventral process (ventral view) and with weakly sclerotized internal structures; parameres approximately 
<quantity box="[854,936,1216,1240]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="32" pageNumber="229" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.3 mm</quantity>
long and with rather large apical lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[854,1460,256,1272]" box="[854,997,1248,1272]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">♀: unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="32.[854,1459,1311,1432]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[854,1065,1311,1336]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bernhauer" authorityYear="1905" box="[1080,1280,1312,1336]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Stichoglossa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="graeca">
<emphasis box="[1080,1280,1312,1336]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Stichoglossa graeca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from other West Palaearctic congeners by its slender (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2019" box="[863,945,1376,1399]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Leptusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="32" pageNumber="229" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[863,945,1376,1399]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Leptusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like) habitus, its coloration, and its small body size alone.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="32" pageNumber="229" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="32.[854,1459,1471,1656]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[854,1208,1471,1496]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">Distribution and natural history</emphasis>
: The species was previously known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1158,1204,1504,1528]" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">type</typeStatus>
locality in the north of the 
<collectingRegion box="[898,1046,1537,1564]" country="Greece" name="Peloponnisos" pageId="32" pageNumber="229">PelopÓnnisos</collectingRegion>
. The male from 
